new, secular Québécois identity. From there, Zubrzycki extends her analysis to the present, looking at the role of Québécois identity in recent debates over immigration, the place of religious symbols in the public sphere, and the politics of cultural heritage-issues that also offer insight on similar debates elsewhere in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChurch and statezQuébec (Province) 0aJohn the Baptist's DayzQuébec (Province) 0aNationalismzQuébec (Province) 0aParadesxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province) 0aSecularismxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province) 0aSocial changezQuébec (Province) 4aQuebec. 4aSt.Jean-Baptiste Holiday. 4anational identity. 4anationalism. 4areligion. 4asecularism. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226391717423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226391717.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles